data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count check with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — tells you *what* the count was on failure, not just "false"
- **`CollectionAssert`** — use for richer collection checks:
  ```csharp
  CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));  // .NET 8+
  CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);                       // reference check
  CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);                     // same items, any order
  ```
- **Add message parameters** — `Assert.IsTrue(condition, "why")` so failures are self-explanatory
- **Avoid `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)`** — use `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` instead
